### Error Handling with Try/Catch

The `try/catch` statement lets you **handle errors** gracefully without crashing your program.

---

### Basic Syntax

```js
try {
  // Code that might throw an error
  let result = riskyOperation();
  console.log(result);
} catch (error) {
  // Code that runs if an error occurs
  console.error("Something went wrong:", error.message);
}
```

---

### The `finally` Block

`finally` runs **regardless** of whether an error occurred or not:

```js
try {
  console.log("Trying...");
  throw new Error("Oops!");
} catch (error) {
  console.log("Caught:", error.message);
} finally {
  console.log("This always runs!");
}
```

---

### The Error Object

When an error occurs, JavaScript provides an **Error object** with properties:

| Property | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `name` | Type of error (e.g., `ReferenceError`) |
| `message` | Human-readable description |
| `stack` | Call stack trace (useful for debugging) |

---

### Error Types

- `Error` -- Generic error
- `ReferenceError` -- Accessing undefined variable
- `TypeError` -- Wrong type used
- `SyntaxError` -- Invalid syntax (cannot be caught in try/catch)
- `RangeError` -- Value out of range

---

> **Best Practice:** Always handle errors in asynchronous code (API calls, file operations, etc.). Unhandled errors can crash your application.

codeExample:
try {
  let result = 10 / 0;
  console.log(result);
  console.log(undefinedVariable); // This causes an error
} catch (err) {
  console.log("Error caught:", err.message);
} finally {
  console.log("Cleanup code runs here");
}
